---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="PRI Methodology — Narrows"
  description="Full technical documentation for the Narrows Port Risk Index: data sources, indicator definitions, normalisation procedures, and composite scoring."
>

<style>
.meth-hero {
  padding: 120px var(--s4) var(--s5);
  max-width: var(--max-w);
  margin: 0 auto;
}
.meth-hero-kicker {
  display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 10px;
  font-size: 10px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.16em; text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--text-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--s2);
}
.meth-hero-kicker::before { content: ''; width: 32px; height: 1px; background: var(--gold); }
.meth-hero h1 {
  font-size: clamp(28px, 3.5vw, 46px); font-weight: 700; color: var(--navy);
  line-height: 1.1; letter-spacing: -0.03em; margin-bottom: var(--s2);
}
.meth-hero-lead {
  font-size: 17px; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.7;
  font-weight: 300; max-width: 620px; margin-bottom: var(--s3);
}
.meth-meta {
  display: flex; gap: var(--s3); flex-wrap: wrap;
  font-size: 12px; color: var(--text-tertiary);
}
.meth-meta-item::before { content: '·'; margin-right: 6px; }
.meth-meta-item:first-child::before { content: ''; margin-right: 0; }

/* Two-column layout: sticky TOC + content */
.meth-body {
  max-width: var(--max-w); margin: 0 auto;
  padding: 0 var(--s4) var(--s6);
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 220px 1fr;
  gap: 64px;
  align-items: start;
}
.meth-toc {
  position: sticky; top: 88px;
}
.meth-toc-title {
  font-size: 9px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.14em; text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--text-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--s2); padding-bottom: var(--s1);
  border-bottom: var(--rule-light);
}
.meth-toc ol { list-style: none; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 2px; }
.meth-toc a {
  font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-secondary); text-decoration: none;
  line-height: 1.5; display: block; padding: 4px 0; transition: color 0.15s;
}
.meth-toc a:hover { color: var(--navy); }

/* Sections */
.meth-section {
  border-top: var(--rule-light); padding-top: var(--s4); margin-bottom: var(--s5);
}
.meth-section:first-of-type { border-top: none; padding-top: 0; }
.meth-section-num {
  font-size: 9px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.14em; text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--text-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--s1);
}
.meth-section h2 {
  font-size: clamp(20px, 2vw, 26px); font-weight: 700; color: var(--navy);
  letter-spacing: -0.02em; margin-bottom: var(--s3); line-height: 1.15;
}
.meth-section h3 {
  font-size: 16px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--navy);
  letter-spacing: -0.01em; margin: var(--s3) 0 var(--s2);
  display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 10px;
}
.dim-dot { width: 10px; height: 10px; border-radius: 50%; flex-shrink: 0; }

.meth-p {
  font-size: 15px; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.75;
  font-weight: 300; margin-bottom: var(--s2);
}
.meth-p strong { color: var(--text-primary); font-weight: 600; }
.meth-p code {
  font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace; font-size: 13px;
  background: var(--surface); padding: 1px 6px; border-radius: 3px; color: var(--navy);
}

/* Formula block */
.meth-formula {
  background: var(--navy); border-radius: 8px;
  padding: var(--s3) var(--s4); margin: var(--s3) 0;
  font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace;
  font-size: 14px; color: var(--gold); letter-spacing: 0.02em; line-height: 1.8;
}
.meth-formula .formula-label {
  font-size: 9px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.12em; text-transform: uppercase;
  color: rgba(255,255,255,0.3); display: block; margin-bottom: 6px;
  font-family: var(--font);
}

/* Indicator tables */
.meth-table-wrap {
  overflow-x: auto; margin: var(--s3) 0;
  border: var(--rule-light); border-radius: 8px;
}
.meth-table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 13px; }
.meth-table thead { background: var(--surface); }
.meth-table th {
  padding: 10px 14px; text-align: left;
  font-size: 9px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--text-tertiary); white-space: nowrap; border-bottom: var(--rule-light);
}
.meth-table td {
  padding: 11px 14px; border-bottom: var(--rule-light);
  color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.55; vertical-align: top;
}
.meth-table tr:last-child td { border-bottom: none; }
.meth-table td:first-child { font-weight: 600; color: var(--navy); white-space: nowrap; }
.meth-table td code {
  font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace; font-size: 11px;
  background: var(--surface); padding: 1px 5px; border-radius: 3px; color: var(--navy);
}

/* Score bands */
.meth-bands {
  display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
  gap: 1px; background: var(--border); border-radius: 8px; overflow: hidden;
  margin: var(--s3) 0;
}
.meth-band {
  padding: 16px 14px; background: var(--white);
  display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 4px;
}
.meth-band-score { font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: -0.02em; }
.meth-band-label { font-size: 12px; font-weight: 600; }
.meth-band-desc { font-size: 11px; color: var(--text-tertiary); line-height: 1.4; margin-top: 2px; }

/* Limitations */
.meth-limits { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--s2); margin: var(--s2) 0; }
.meth-limit {
  display: flex; gap: 14px; padding: var(--s2) var(--s3);
  background: var(--surface); border-radius: 6px; border-left: 3px solid var(--border);
}
.meth-limit-icon { font-size: 15px; flex-shrink: 0; margin-top: 2px; }
.meth-limit-body { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.65; }
.meth-limit-body strong { color: var(--text-primary); font-weight: 600; }

.meth-back {
  display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 6px;
  font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-secondary); text-decoration: none;
  margin-bottom: var(--s4); transition: color 0.15s;
}
.meth-back:hover { color: var(--navy); }

@media (max-width: 900px) {
  .meth-body { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  .meth-toc { display: none; }
  .meth-bands { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); }
}
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  .meth-bands { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
}
</style>

<!-- Hero -->
<div class="meth-hero fade-up">
  <div class="meth-hero-kicker">Technical documentation</div>
  <h1>Port Risk Index<br>Methodology</h1>
  <p class="meth-hero-lead">
    Full specification of the Narrows PRI: data universe, indicator definitions,
    normalisation procedures, composite scoring, and known limitations.
  </p>
  <div class="meth-meta">
    <span class="meth-meta-item">Version 1.1</span>
    <span class="meth-meta-item">May 2026</span>
    <span class="meth-meta-item">3804 ports · 28 fields</span>
    <span class="meth-meta-item">Data vintage 2023/24</span>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="meth-body">

  <!-- TOC -->
  <nav class="meth-toc">
    <div class="meth-toc-title">Contents</div>
    <ol>
      <li><a href="#overview">1. Overview</a></li>
      <li><a href="#universe">2. Data Universe</a></li>
      <li><a href="#composite">3. Composite Scoring</a></li>
      <li><a href="#d1">4. D1: Accessibility</a></li>
      <li><a href="#d2">5. D2: Reliability</a></li>
      <li><a href="#d3">6. D3: Concentration</a></li>
      <li><a href="#d4">7. D4: Stability</a></li>
      <li><a href="#interpretation">8. Score Interpretation</a></li>
      <li><a href="#tiers">9. Data Tiers</a></li>
      <li><a href="#limitations">10. Limitations</a></li>
      <li><a href="#vintage">11. Data Vintage</a></li>
      <li><a href="#cppi">12. Related Indices</a></li>
    </ol>
  </nav>

  <!-- Content -->
  <div>
    <a href="/pri" class="meth-back">← Back to Port Risk Index</a>

    <!-- 1 -->
    <div class="meth-section" id="overview">
      <div class="meth-section-num">Section 1</div>
      <h2>Overview</h2>
      <p class="meth-p">
        The Narrows Port Risk Index (PRI) is a composite risk score assigned to every port in the
        World Port Index universe. It is designed to support comparative risk assessment across a
        global port population: quantifying, in a single number, the relative risk a given port
        poses to a maritime supply chain.
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        The index is structured around <strong>four dimensions</strong>, each capturing a distinct
        class of port risk: physical accessibility, operational reliability, trade concentration, and
        geopolitical and institutional stability. Within each dimension, source indicators are
        normalised to a 0–10 scale and combined into a dimension score. The four dimension scores
        are then composited into a single PRI via <strong>geometric mean</strong>.
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        The geometric mean is standard practice in multi-dimensional risk compositing because it
        penalises dimensional extremes. A port that scores very well on physical access cannot offset
        a severe stability deficit: both the dimension weakness and the composite will reflect the
        exposure. This property is essential in a risk instrument — compensatory arithmetic means
        systematically understate concentrated risk.
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        <strong>Lower PRI score = lower risk.</strong> The empirical range across the 3804-port
        universe is approximately 0.75 to 3.71. Score distributions are right-skewed: the median
        port falls below 1.8, and the large majority of ports fall below 2.0.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- 2 -->
    <div class="meth-section" id="universe">
      <div class="meth-section-num">Section 2</div>
      <h2>Data Universe</h2>
      <p class="meth-p">
        The PRI covers all ports in the <strong>National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency World Port
        Index (WPI), Publication 150</strong> — the standard global port registry used by the
        maritime industry. The WPI lists 3804 ports across 195 countries, from major transshipment
        hubs to small coastal facilities.
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        The WPI provides port-level attributes including controlling depth, terminal count, and
        vessel class acceptances. These attributes anchor D1 (Accessibility) scoring. Country-level
        indicators from external sources are matched to each port via ISO-2 country code and
        geographic coordinates.
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        Not all ports have complete data across all dimensions. Where source data is unavailable
        for a given indicator, the scoring procedure applies a conservative imputation — typically
        the global mean or a data-tier-adjusted estimate. Coverage quality is captured in the
        <code>data_tier</code> and <code>n_dims</code> fields (see Section 9).
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- 3 -->
    <div class="meth-section" id="composite">
      <div class="meth-section-num">Section 3</div>
      <h2>Composite Scoring</h2>
      <p class="meth-p">
        Each dimension produces a score on a 0–10 scale. The composite PRI is the geometric mean
        of the four dimension scores, with a floor of 0.1 applied to each dimension before
        compositing to prevent zero values from collapsing the result.
      </p>
      <div class="meth-formula">
        <span class="formula-label">Composite formula</span>
        PRI = (D1 × D2 × D3 × D4) ^ (1/4)<br><br>
        where each Dₙ = max(raw_dimension_score, 0.1)
      </div>
      <p class="meth-p">
        Within each dimension, indicators are normalised and combined. The normalisation approach
        varies by indicator type:
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        <strong>Continuous indicators</strong> (depth, LPI score, PGA values) are min-max
        normalised against the empirical range of the full WPI population and rescaled to 0–10.
        For risk indicators, direction is inverted so higher raw values (higher hazard) map to
        higher scores (higher risk).
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        <strong>Count indicators</strong> (terminal count, vessel class count) are scored via a
        stepped function mapping discrete counts to risk levels. Higher counts receive lower scores
        — more capacity and redundancy means lower risk.
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        <strong>Ordinal indicators</strong> (labour regime, sanctions level, dispute level) are
        mapped from categorical values to numeric scores via fixed scoring tables, documented in
        the indicator sections below.
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        The composite PRI is not rescaled back to 0–10. Because the structural moderation of D1
        — most ports have serviceable physical infrastructure — the empirical maximum is 3.71
        rather than 10. This is intentional: the score preserves the absolute signal from
        individual dimensions rather than normalising it away.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- 4 D1 -->
    <div class="meth-section" id="d1">
      <div class="meth-section-num">Section 4</div>
      <h2>D1: Accessibility</h2>
      <h3><span class="dim-dot" style="background:#378ADD"></span>Physical access risk</h3>
      <p class="meth-p">
        D1 measures the inherent physical constraints on port access and the natural hazard
        exposure of the port location. A port scores higher on D1 if it has limited depth, cannot
        accommodate large vessel classes, has few terminals, or faces elevated cyclone or seismic
        risk.
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        Physical access risk is the most structurally stable dimension: it changes only when ports
        invest in infrastructure or when hazard assessments are updated. It also has the most
        consistent data coverage across the WPI universe, since the WPI itself captures the core
        physical attributes.
      </p>

      <div class="meth-table-wrap">
        <table class="meth-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Field</th>
              <th>Description</th>
              <th>Source</th>
              <th>Risk direction</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><code>ctrl_depth_final</code></td>
              <td>Controlling depth in metres. The minimum depth across approach channel, anchorage, and berth. Determines maximum vessel draft.</td>
              <td>WPI Pub. 150</td>
              <td>Shallower = higher risk</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>vessel_class_count</code></td>
              <td>Number of vessel classes the port explicitly accepts per WPI (general cargo, tankers, bulk carriers, container ships, Ro-Ro, passenger).</td>
              <td>WPI Pub. 150</td>
              <td>Fewer classes = higher risk</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>terminal_count</code></td>
              <td>Number of distinct terminal facilities. Higher counts indicate operational redundancy and lower single-point concentration within the port.</td>
              <td>WPI Pub. 150</td>
              <td>Fewer terminals = higher risk</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>cyclone_passes</code></td>
              <td>Count of historical tropical cyclone tracks (Category 3+ Saffir-Simpson) passing within 250 km of the port, drawn from the full IBTrACS record (1842–2023).</td>
              <td>IBTrACS v04r01 (NOAA)</td>
              <td>More passes = higher risk</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>pga_g</code></td>
              <td>Peak ground acceleration at 10% exceedance probability in 50 years, in units of g. From the USGS Global Seismic Hazard model at 0.1-degree resolution.</td>
              <td>USGS PSHA (Petersen et al.)</td>
              <td>Higher PGA = higher risk</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="meth-p">
        The five D1 source fields are normalised individually, then combined via unweighted
        arithmetic mean to produce the D1 dimension score.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- 5 D2 -->
    <div class="meth-section" id="d2">
      <div class="meth-section-num">Section 5</div>
      <h2>D2: Reliability</h2>
      <h3><span class="dim-dot" style="background:#EF9F27"></span>Operational reliability risk</h3>
      <p class="meth-p">
        D2 measures the operational environment at country and port level: how efficiently cargo
        moves through the port, how reliable the surrounding logistics network is, and whether
        labour conditions create structural friction. A port scores higher on D2 if it sits in a
        country with weak logistics performance, has elevated dwell times, or operates under an
        unstable labour regime.
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        D2 is the most country-dependent dimension. The World Bank LPI is a country-level
        composite, meaning ports within the same country share an LPI score. Port-level
        differentiation within a country is introduced via dwell time and labour regime where
        port-specific data is available.
      </p>

      <div class="meth-table-wrap">
        <table class="meth-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Field</th>
              <th>Description</th>
              <th>Source</th>
              <th>Risk direction</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><code>lpi_score</code></td>
              <td>World Bank Logistics Performance Index overall score (1–5 scale). Covers customs efficiency, infrastructure quality, ease of arranging shipments, logistics service quality, tracking capability, and timeliness. Applied at country level.</td>
              <td>World Bank LPI 2023</td>
              <td>Lower LPI = higher risk</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>dwell_hours</code></td>
              <td>Estimated average container dwell time in hours. Derived from a Narrows dwell-time index combining World Bank port performance data and industry benchmarks. Country-level estimates are used where port-specific data is unavailable.</td>
              <td>World Bank PPPI, industry sources</td>
              <td>Longer dwell = higher risk</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>labour_regime</code></td>
              <td>Categorical assessment of port labour environment. Values: <code>stable</code>, <code>disputed</code>, <code>volatile</code>. Derived from strike history, union concentration, and labour dispute records. Ordinal map: stable = 1.0, disputed = 5.5, volatile = 9.0 (on 0–10 risk scale).</td>
              <td>ILO, national labour records</td>
              <td>Volatile = highest risk</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="meth-p">
        The three D2 indicators are combined via weighted arithmetic mean, with LPI carrying the
        highest weight given its methodological rigour and global coverage.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- 6 D3 -->
    <div class="meth-section" id="d3">
      <div class="meth-section-num">Section 6</div>
      <h2>D3: Concentration</h2>
      <h3><span class="dim-dot" style="background:#7F77DD"></span>Trade concentration risk</h3>
      <p class="meth-p">
        D3 measures how dependent a port's catchment economy is on a narrow set of trades or
        commodities, and how substitutable the port is if it became unavailable. A port scores
        higher on D3 if it serves a highly specialised hinterland, if it dominates its catchment
        with few alternatives nearby, or if trade is concentrated in a small number of commodity
        categories.
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        Concentration risk is the dimension most likely to be underestimated in qualitative
        assessments. Ports that appear operationally sound can carry severe systemic risk if their
        catchment is a mono-commodity economy with no viable alternative port within a realistic
        rerouting radius.
      </p>

      <div class="meth-table-wrap">
        <table class="meth-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Field</th>
              <th>Description</th>
              <th>Source</th>
              <th>Risk direction</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><code>catchment_share_pct</code></td>
              <td>Estimated share of the port's national or sub-national hinterland trade volume flowing through this single port. High values indicate gateway concentration: a port outage has outsized national impact.</td>
              <td>UN Comtrade, WPI, Narrows catchment model</td>
              <td>Higher share = higher risk</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>herfindahl</code></td>
              <td>Herfindahl-Hirschman Index calculated across commodity categories in the port's trade flows (range 0–1). A value approaching 1.0 indicates near-total dependence on a single commodity.</td>
              <td>UN Comtrade HS-2 aggregation</td>
              <td>Higher HHI = higher risk</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>alt_distance_km</code></td>
              <td>Great-circle distance in kilometres to the nearest alternative port capable of handling the same vessel classes. Longer distance means fewer viable alternatives and higher concentration risk.</td>
              <td>WPI, Narrows routing model</td>
              <td>Longer distance = higher risk</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="meth-p">
        The three D3 indicators are combined via unweighted arithmetic mean. D3 is the dimension
        most sensitive to trade flow data quality. UN Comtrade data is incomplete or significantly
        delayed for a non-trivial fraction of the WPI universe — particularly in smaller island
        economies and parts of Sub-Saharan Africa. These gaps are captured in the data tier system.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- 7 D4 -->
    <div class="meth-section" id="d4">
      <div class="meth-section-num">Section 7</div>
      <h2>D4: Stability</h2>
      <h3><span class="dim-dot" style="background:#D85A30"></span>Geopolitical and institutional risk</h3>
      <p class="meth-p">
        D4 measures the political and institutional environment in which the port operates. A port
        scores higher on D4 if it sits in a country with weak rule of law and poor governance, is
        subject to active international sanctions, or sits within a territory affected by an
        unresolved maritime or territorial dispute.
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        D4 has the highest volatility relative to the other dimensions: political conditions can
        shift rapidly. The PRI D4 score should be read as a structural baseline, not a real-time
        political risk monitor. Users requiring live sanctions screening should supplement the
        index with a dedicated screening service.
      </p>

      <div class="meth-table-wrap">
        <table class="meth-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Field</th>
              <th>Description</th>
              <th>Source</th>
              <th>Risk direction</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><code>wgi_ps</code></td>
              <td>World Bank WGI Political Stability and Absence of Violence sub-index. Standard normal units (typically -2.5 to +2.5). Higher values indicate greater stability. Rescaled to 0–10 for compositing.</td>
              <td>World Bank WGI 2023</td>
              <td>Lower WGI = higher risk</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>wgi_ge</code></td>
              <td>World Bank WGI Government Effectiveness sub-index. Captures perceptions of public service quality, civil service independence, and policy credibility. Same scale and rescaling as wgi_ps.</td>
              <td>World Bank WGI 2023</td>
              <td>Lower WGI = higher risk</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>sanctions_level</code></td>
              <td>Active international sanctions exposure affecting the port's country or port directly. Values: <code>none</code>, <code>partial</code>, <code>comprehensive</code>. Ordinal map: none = 0, partial = 5.0, comprehensive = 10.0. Derived from OFAC SDN list, EU Consolidated List, and UN Security Council resolutions.</td>
              <td>OFAC, EU OJ, UN SC</td>
              <td>Comprehensive = highest risk</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>dispute_level</code></td>
              <td>Active territorial or maritime boundary disputes affecting the port's operating jurisdiction. Values: <code>none</code>, <code>latent</code>, <code>active</code>. Ordinal map: none = 0, latent = 3.5, active = 8.5. Sourced from ICJ dockets and UNCLOS arbitration records.</td>
              <td>ICJ, PCA, UNCLOS records</td>
              <td>Active = highest risk</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="meth-p">
        The four D4 indicators are combined via unweighted arithmetic mean.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- 8 -->
    <div class="meth-section" id="interpretation">
      <div class="meth-section-num">Section 8</div>
      <h2>Score Interpretation</h2>
      <p class="meth-p">
        The PRI is a relative risk measure, not an absolute probability of disruption. It supports
        comparison within and across port populations. The following bands reflect the empirical
        distribution of the 3804-port universe.
      </p>

      <div class="meth-bands">
        <div class="meth-band">
          <span class="meth-band-score" style="color:#378ADD">Below 1.2</span>
          <span class="meth-band-label" style="color:#378ADD">Low risk</span>
          <span class="meth-band-desc">Top quartile globally. Strong across all four dimensions. Singapore, Rotterdam, Hamburg.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="meth-band">
          <span class="meth-band-score" style="color:#1565A8">1.2 – 2.0</span>
          <span class="meth-band-label" style="color:#1565A8">Moderate risk</span>
          <span class="meth-band-desc">The bulk of the global port population. Adequate infrastructure with some dimensional weakness.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="meth-band">
          <span class="meth-band-score" style="color:#EF9F27">2.0 – 2.8</span>
          <span class="meth-band-label" style="color:#EF9F27">Elevated risk</span>
          <span class="meth-band-desc">Material weakness in one or more dimensions. Warrants attention in supply chain risk assessments.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="meth-band">
          <span class="meth-band-score" style="color:#D85A30">Above 2.8</span>
          <span class="meth-band-label" style="color:#D85A30">High risk</span>
          <span class="meth-band-desc">Severe weakness across multiple dimensions. Conflict-zone ports, comprehensively sanctioned ports, isolated mono-commodity gateways.</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="meth-p">
        Dimension scores should always be read alongside the composite. Two ports with identical
        composite scores can have very different risk profiles: a port scoring 2.0 evenly across
        all four dimensions is categorically different from one scoring 0.5/0.5/0.5/9.0. The
        composite captures the systemic risk level; the dimension breakdown shows where the risk
        is concentrated.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- 9 -->
    <div class="meth-section" id="tiers">
      <div class="meth-section-num">Section 9</div>
      <h2>Data Tiers</h2>
      <p class="meth-p">
        The <code>data_tier</code> field (A, B, or C) reflects overall data coverage quality for
        each port. It is a summary signal, not an additional risk score.
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        <strong>Tier A:</strong> Full primary data across all four dimensions. The composite PRI
        is based entirely on directly sourced indicators. Approximately 60% of the WPI universe.
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        <strong>Tier B:</strong> Partial gaps in one or two dimensions, filled with country-level
        or imputed estimates. The composite is reliable but carries additional uncertainty in the
        affected dimensions.
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        <strong>Tier C:</strong> Significant gaps in three or more dimensions. The composite
        should be treated as an indicative estimate. Tier C ports are typically very small
        facilities for which public source data is sparse.
      </p>
      <p class="meth-p">
        The <code>n_dims</code> field records how many of the four dimension scores are based on
        complete primary data (0–4), providing more granular coverage information than the tier alone.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- 10 -->
    <div class="meth-section" id="limitations">
      <div class="meth-section-num">Section 10</div>
      <h2>Known Limitations</h2>
      <p class="meth-p">
        The PRI is built on the best publicly available source data. The following limitations
        are inherent to the current version and should inform how the index is used.
      </p>

      <div class="meth-limits">
        <div class="meth-limit">
          <div class="meth-limit-icon">⚠</div>
          <div class="meth-limit-body">
            <strong>Country-level proxies for port-level conditions.</strong>
            LPI, WGI, and trade flow data are country-level indicators matched to individual ports.
            Within large countries (China, USA, Brazil), there can be substantial port-to-port
            variation that national indices cannot capture. D2 and D4 scores for ports within the
            same country will be identical unless port-specific data is available.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="meth-limit">
          <div class="meth-limit-icon">⚠</div>
          <div class="meth-limit-body">
            <strong>Static snapshot, not a real-time monitor.</strong>
            The PRI is updated annually. Sudden political shocks, port closures, or sanctions
            actions will not be reflected until the next update cycle. D4 scores in particular
            should be treated as a structural baseline.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="meth-limit">
          <div class="meth-limit-icon">⚠</div>
          <div class="meth-limit-body">
            <strong>Trade concentration data gaps.</strong>
            UN Comtrade data is unavailable, delayed, or unreliable for a non-trivial fraction
            of the WPI universe. D3 scores for Tier B and C ports in affected regions rely on
            imputed estimates and carry higher uncertainty.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="meth-limit">
          <div class="meth-limit-icon">⚠</div>
          <div class="meth-limit-body">
            <strong>Equal dimensional weighting.</strong>
            The geometric mean treats each dimension as equally important. This is a reasonable
            default but different supply chain contexts may warrant different relative weights.
            Custom weighting is available on the Narrows platform for commercial users.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="meth-limit">
          <div class="meth-limit-icon">⚠</div>
          <div class="meth-limit-body">
            <strong>WPI port universe only.</strong>
            The PRI covers only ports listed in WPI Publication 150. Small craft facilities,
            river jetties, and offshore terminals not in the WPI are not scored.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- 11 -->
    <div class="meth-section" id="vintage">
      <div class="meth-section-num">Section 11</div>
      <h2>Data Vintage and Update Cadence</h2>
      <p class="meth-p">
        The current PRI (v1.1, May 2026) uses the following source vintages.
      </p>

      <div class="meth-table-wrap">
        <table class="meth-table">
